<font color="#FF0000">A MONUMENT FOR ALL PEOPLE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec  3 18:53:20 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I read in one of the entries above from Chris that he was surprised that Vietnamese individuals visit the Viet Nam war memorial.  She was suprised that two enemies could speak years later about it.  I must correct her.  Not all the Vietnamese in Viet Nam were the &quot;enemy.&quot;  For every American soldier that was killed, countless Vietnamese soliders also died as they fought together, on the same side.  It is a misconception that American soldiers fought to liberate the Vietnamese from oppression.  The Vietnamese people did not stand idly by and allow American boys to die in their stead.  My father was a naval officer who fought on the side of FREEDOM, and he does not consider Americans the enemy.  My mother lost her only brother to this war, and he was killed by a Viet Cong, like countless American GI's.<br>
If the monument represents anything, it is that there is no good guy or bad guy in war.  It is not an American monument, but a monument for the world to learn from.  The victor suffers no less than the defeated.  Ask any Vietnamese-American who lost the war, and he would tell you Viet Nam lost.  She lost her freedom, her life, her prosperity, her people.<br>
I was only eight months old when my family left Viet Nam, but I also have pain and tears to shed, and to share.  Let's work to correct the misconceptions that work to make us adversaries, and instead work for a better world.
